    "narrative": "The offense is anchored today by **Mickey Moniak**, our strongest play with a 73.38 rating, fueled by his lead-off spot and a massive 14% park-factor boost. While Brazob\u00e1n is a concern behind the dish, **Mickey Moniak**\u2019s elite speed profile makes him a priority start in our quest to claw back ground in the stolen base category. **Josh Naylor** (70.19) and **Vinnie Pasquantino** (69.46) follow closely; both benefit significantly from dynamic platoon advantages against right-handed starters, with **Vinnie Pasquantino** specifically projected to thrive against Bibee. **Seiya Suzuki** also warrants attention, as he draws the softest matchup of the day against Petty (6.57 xERA), providing a robust 68.88 score that makes him a must-start despite the neutral situational context.\n\nThe bench decision process was tightest at the 2B/MI slots, where **Cole Young** (46.11) narrowly missed the cut. While **Cole Young** offers a solid baseline, he was squeezed out by the efficiency of **Travis Bazzana**, whose SP-skill rating (+13%) and favorable platoon profile gave him the edge in our rotation. We are actively fading **Austin Riley** (42.29) today, as the matchup against Gilbert, L is simply too taxing on his projection, pushing him below our preferred threshold. We remain cautious with **Jose Caballero** (50.32); despite his elite speed, the combination of a bottom-of-the-order assignment and a negative platoon split against Baz suppresses his output. Keep a close watch on **Kyle Karros** (45.39), as his score is vulnerable to the high-percentage pickoff threat posed by the opposing catcher, which creates an inherent risk to our SB-heavy strategy.",
